post_text:
Duluth East defeated Proctor 3-0 in a high school boys soccer match Thursday night at beautiful Ordean Stadium.

Kai Hoffman, Beckett Sherman and Grady Downs had goals for the Greyhounds, who improved to 4-0 and still haven't allowed a goal-against all season.

Duluth East will next play host to Hibbing-Chisholm at 3 p.m. Saturday.

post_text:
Striker Kamryn Hill scored a pair of goals and goalkeeper Mary Johnson posted a shutout to power Denfeld past Proctor 3-0 in a Lake Superior Conference high girls soccer opener for both teams Friday afternoon at historic Public Schools Stadium.

Cora Samuelson also scored for the Hunters (1-0), who are scheduled to next play host to Duluth East on Sept. 11 at PSS..

"We went hunting and played well," Denfeld coach Brandon Sternwedel said after the game. "We were really strong defensively -- give credit to our defenders who really worked their tails off sometimes with only four players back at some points during the match. Our strong team and individual defensive play allowed our attackers to enjoy more free play in their games, and to have fun."

Proctor defeated Denfeld 2-0 in the junior varsity opener.

Duluth Public Schools Photos: Denfeld Varsity and JV game photos. Click on any thumbnail for a larger view.

post_text:
Student Athletes Adjust to "Unique" Fall Season
Denfeld boy's soccer coach Scott Anderson instructed his players to stay six feet apart as they met near midfield at historic Public Schools Stadium during their first preseason workout this week. The Hunters, led by senior forward Keegan Chastey, expect to field one of their best teams in several years this fall.
“We’re dividing our players into four pods," said Anderson. "They’ll socially distance when they’re off the field and use masks when they’re coming and going, all those little things that we’ve got to do. It’s all certainly unique, unexpected, but at the same time we’re just happy to be here, happy to be outside on beautiful summer days and kicking the ball around.”
#Inspire709 #HunterPride
www.ISD709.org/Denfeld

BACK TO SCHOOL GET TOGETHER!
A beautiful evening for a neighborhood get together, hosted by the Duluth Community Schools Collaborative. The event required masks and social distancing - even so, lots of warm conversation and smiling eyes. Free grab and go meals, giveaways, opportunities to learn about parent leadership, the Education Equity Alliance, Duluth NAACP and more. Also a chance to meet and talk with new Denfeld Principal Tom Tusken, Assistant Principal Joanna Walters, Superintendent John Magas, Assistant Superintendent Anthony Bonds, Board members Jill Lofald and Alanna Oswald.
Denfeld High School, Lincoln Park Middle School and Myers-Wilkins Elementary are Duluth Community Schools.
#Inspire709 #CommunitySupport
www.ISD709.org

"Today is Juneteenth Freedom Day in Minnesota. As we observe this day, we are both joyful for the progress we’ve made and somber for all that is left still to do. Juneteenth is the oldest known regular celebration commemorating the ending of slavery in the United States that is celebrated across the country."

shared_text:
Minnesota Department of Education
June 19 at 3:21 PM ·

Today is Juneteenth Freedom Day in Minnesota. As we observe this day, we are both joyful for the progress we’ve made and somber for all that is left still to do. Juneteenth is the oldest known regular celebration commemorating the ending of slavery in the United States that is celebrated across the country. It began on June 19, 1865 when enslaved people in Texas learned of President Lincoln’s Emancipation Proclamation. As the most remote of the Confederate states, Texas was the last state to have the proclamation announced after the end of the Civil War. It was two and a half years after the law had taken effect.

You can celebrate Juneteenth by spending some time learning more about the history and evolution of this holiday. https://nmaahc.si.edu/blog-post/historical-legacy-juneteenth

Minnesota Department of Education
June 12 at 6:00 PM ·

As educators, we must continue to work hard to ensure all students feel safe, welcome and included in our classrooms and our schools. As Education Commissioner Mary Cathryn Ricker says, “we can’t expect our students to conform to our comfort.”

Today, as we honor Pride Month and remember those lost in the Pulse Nightclub Shooting, we are rededicating ourselves to the continued work of lifting up and supporting our LGBTQ+ students and colleagues.

post_text:
Minnesota Governor Tim Walz proclaims June 15, 2020 Elias Clayton, Elmer Jackson and Isaac McGhie Commemoration Day.
"Today, we remember Elias Clayton, Elmer Jackson, and Isaac McGhie. It has been 100 years since they were lynched by a white mob in Duluth after they were falsely accused of a crime. We cannot allow such communal atrocities to happen again."
shared_text:
Minnesota Department of Education
June 15 at 2:36 PM ·

Today, we remember Elias Clayton, Elmer Jackson, and Isaac McGhie. It has been 100 years since they were lynched by a white mob in Duluth after they were falsely accused of a crime. We cannot allow such communal atrocities to happen again. At 12:30 p.m. the Minnesota Historical Society will be premiering “Perspectives on the Legacy of the Duluth Lynchings,” a compilation video featuring perspectives from Minnesota historians, celebrated authors, and prominent community members about the tragic history of the Duluth lynchings on their Facebook page. In addition the Minnesota Historical Society has educational resources about the tragic events of June 15, 1920 at https://www.mnhs.org/duluthlynchings/.

Minnesota Department of Education
June 10 at 5:38 PM ·

We’re proud to recognize 67 schools and six school districts for their successful work using Positive Behavioral Intervention and Supports (PBIS), a data-driven program that provides schools and districts with training and support to promote positive student behavior, especially for students facing challenges inside and outside of the classroom. Through evidence-based practices, this national program aims to make schools more responsive to the cultures and communities they serve. One important area of focus for the program is on decreasing disparities in discipline, which have historically had negative impacts on educational outcomes for students of color, American Indian students and students with disabilities. The schools receiving recognition are leaders in supporting positive behavior, improving school climate and increasing student achievement. Read more: https://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/MNMDE/bulletins/28fec15

shared_text:
Minnesota Department of Human Services
June 8 at 8:04 PM ·

Parents – who were NOT receiving SNAP or MFIP benefits on March 18, 2020 – can now apply for temporary food support for children who receive free or reduced-price school meals. Apply online at mn.p-ebt.org by June 30, 2020.

Eligible families will receive a P-EBT card in the mail within 30 days. Families on SNAP or MFIP on March 18 do not need to apply; benefits were already issued to their EBT cards.

For more information, see https://mn.gov/dhs/p-ebt/.

post_text:
Honoring the Class of 2020
American Indian Graduating Seniors were honored at Denfeld and Duluth East High Schools this week. Angela Buffalo is Chairperson for the American Indian Parent Advisory Committee (AIEPAC), she says it's good for students to be acknowledged and respected for their work.
"Lots of smiles, lots of pictures, family," says Buffalo. She encourages people to get involved, be good mentors, open their minds to culture. "And please come to a meeting, we encourage people to join."
AIEPAC meeting schedules and additional information are available online: https://bit.ly/2Y2V3uw
Duluth American Indian Education Program's mission is to promote youth leadership, provide academic support and encourage career development for American Indian students based on American Indian values, culture and language.
Duluth American Indian Education: https://bit.ly/30dZSUg
Thank you, JP Rennquist, for the photos.

post_text:
UPDATE: ISD 709 STUDENT ACCOUNTS
The ISD 709 Technology Department expects student accounts to be active by noon today Thursday 6/4.
>>Students will be able to access their accounts using their existing passwords for grades K-5 and 9-12.
>>Students in Grades 6 – 8 will receive information from their school as to how to login to their account.
On Wednesday 6/3 we received a report from one of our students of an unauthorized attempt to sign in to their ISD 709 account.
Our Technology Department staff began investigating and over the course of the afternoon identified 14 student accounts being accessed by outside IP accounts. To prevent any additional unauthorized logins Technology staff disabled all student accounts and worked to address the breach.
We have not seen any suspicious activity from the compromised student accounts but we will continue to monitor and investigate.
Thank you for your patience and for your support.

post_text:
Sharing a message from Bill Gronseth, Superintendent, Duluth Public Schools:
"The tragedy that occurred in Minneapolis involving the death of George Floyd is heart wrenching. It highlights once more the injustice, inequity and racism in our society and further emphasizes the need for systemic change throughout our country. This includes our Duluth Public Schools, and the ongoing work necessary to eliminate institutional barriers to educational opportunity.
We have been sharing messages of support and resources with our families and staff in response to Mr. Floyd's death. The following link has links to resources that may be helpful as you support the young people who may be reaching out to you."
https://bit.ly/2Aszs6t
www.ISD709.org
shared_text:
ISD709.ORG
Superintendent Message George Floyd
text:
Sharing a message from Bill Gronseth, Superintendent, Duluth Public Schools:
"The tragedy that occurred in Minneapolis involving the death of George Floyd is heart wrenching. It highlights once more the injustice, inequity and racism in our society and further emphasizes the need for systemic change throughout our country. This includes our Duluth Public Schools, and the ongoing work necessary to eliminate institutional barriers to educational opportunity.
We have been sharing messages of support and resources with our families and staff in response to Mr. Floyd's death. The following link has links to resources that may be helpful as you support the young people who may be reaching out to you."
https://bit.ly/2Aszs6t
www.ISD709.org

ISD709.ORG
Superintendent Message George Floyd

DENFELD STUDENTS MAKE ALL-STATE, QUALIFY FOR NATIONALS!
Congratulations Abigail Longnaker and Sydney Rabold, named to the All-State Speech Team by the Minnesota Speech Coaches Association. Qualifications to achieve this appointment are strict - they must be a 4 year member of the team, have competed at the MSHSL State Speech Tournament two years and have placed in the top 6 speakers in their event in 8 tournaments over two seasons.
Both of these seniors also qualified for the National Tournament of Champions that would have been held this month in Houston, Texas. Due to the COVID-19 pandemic this event has been cancelled.

THANK YOU, FACILITIES & MAINTENANCE STAFF!
Many thanks for the work they do each day, cleaning and sanitizing buildings and schools throughout the pandemic.
"They care about keeping buildings safe," says Heather Ashbaugh, Supervisor of Building Operations. "They impress me every day, with ideas that go over and above MDH and CDC guidelines. They work in the buildings, they know the buildings and what needs to be done."
"We care, we're here to make this a clean, safe environment," says Thomas Esse, Chief Engineer for Duluth East High School. "My crew goes the extra mile, we do what we have to do to take every situation into consideration."
Like all of us, Esse says, "We'll be happy when the normal times start again and the kids are back."
#Inspire709

post_text:
Denfeld counselor Jessica Anderson and a team of teachers and staff visited senior students' homes Friday morning to deliver yard signs, graduation caps and gowns and yearbooks.

"I think it's been tough and challenging for our students, but I know they're trying to be positive and put on a smile and a brave face and try to make the most of it," Anderson said of the COVID-19 pandemic, before venturing out into the West Duluth, Lincoln Park, Piedmont Heights and Duluth Heights neighborhoods. "Teachers and staff are all super, super excited to see our students and make that connection with the social distancing in place and just seeing the smiles on their faces and actually seeing them in person because it's been a few months now."

Duluth Public Schools photo

DULUTH PUBLIC SCHOOLS ALUMNI, RETIRED STAFF

At least three former Duluth Public Schools alumni and retired teachers brought Enger Park Golf Course to its knees on Friday afternoon.

Participating in back-to-back foursomes were elite senior golfers:

. 91-year-old Ken Sunnarborg, a shooting guard on the 1947 Duluth Denfeld state championship basketball team

. Tom Stone, 81, a retired teacher and boys basketball coach at Duluth Denfeld and assistant principal at Lincoln Park Middle School

. Dave Griffin, 76, a retired teacher at various Duluth Public Schools high schools and middle schools for 36 years.

Duluth Public Schools photos of Sunnarborg, Stone and Griffin are below.

Ordean East PTA
April 21 at 2:21 AM ·

We were disappointed to cancel the presentation of Screenagers: Next Chapter this past March. However- we are THRILLED to offer an online streaming version for FREE. Click on the link below and register to view the second movie in the Screenagers series.
Filmmaker and physician Dr. Delaney Ruston takes the conversation around screens and teens to the next level with Screenagers NEXT CHAPTER: Uncovering Skills for Stress Resilience—a film that examines the science behind teen’s emotional challenges, the interplay of social media, and most importantly, what can be done in our schools and homes to help them build crucial skills to navigate stress, anxiety, and depression in our digital age. Access to the film is available until May 11!

https://www.bigmarker.com/screenagers-starhouse/SCREENAGERS-NC-STREAM-OrdeanEastMiddleSchoolPTA

THANK YOU, DULUTH SCHOOL LIBRARY MEDIA SPECIALISTS!
Governor's Proclamation: https://bit.ly/34Om2Nl
April 20 is School Library Media Specialists Day in Minnesota.
These professional educators provide students with the skills they need to access and use information throughout their lives. They work alongside school district administrators, teachers in every content area, and technology personnel facing the unique challenges currently taking place during distance learning. They give guidance in selecting and curating print and electronic resources, promote information, digital, and traditional literacies to students, and teach digital citizenship and cybersecurity. Through this work, they contribute to an interest in life-long learning and enhance the quality of life. Many thanks for all you do!
#Inspire709 #RockStars
www.ISD709.org

shared_text:
City of Duluth, MN Government
April 18 at 9:02 PM ·

We believe that everyone counts. To date 55% of Duluthians have taken the Census. That leaves 45% who have not yet taken it. When you are talking to your friends, coworkers, classmates, and family members please ask if they have taken the Census. Duluth like other cities relies on our response to help fund essential services that we all benefit from. So be counted, and help your friends to be counted too. Head to my2020census.gov now.
#2020Census #WeCountMN

post_text:
Cloth Face Coverings Arriving Each Day!
Many thanks for the community response to our request for cloth face coverings for essential employees.
They're being used by people making and delivering free breakfast and lunch, working in emergency childcare, sanitizing buildings and working on curriculum packet distribution.
There's still a need. If you or your organization are making cloth face coverings, please consider donating them toward this work. If you’re able to help, items can be dropped off at the Third Street entrance of Historic Old Central HS, 215 N. 1st Ave East. Questions: email covidquestions@isd709.org or call 218-336-8740.
CDC Cloth Face Covering Info - includes sew and no-sew instructions: https://bit.ly/3exmLqm
Note, CDC guidance specifically says the cloth face coverings recommended are not surgical masks or N-95 respirators. Those are critical supplies that must continue to be reserved for healthcare workers and other medical first responders, as recommended by current CDC guidance.

MONDAYS: DENFELD, DULUTH EAST #BeTheLightMN
Both high schools join #BeTheLightMN as a sign of hope, and to honor and encourage the Class of 2020, students and community. Lights at Historic Public Schools Stadium and Ordean Stadium will be on at 8:20PM for 20 minutes on Monday nights. Please enjoy from afar and respect social distancing, fields are not open to the public during this time.
From John Millea, MN State High School League, “We're all still here. We're going to be back under the lights at an event — at some point we're going to be able to gather again, and it's going to be great once we get back to that point. But I think just for now, it's just a symbol ... that there's still light out there and there's hope. And what we're going through now isn't going to last forever."

post_text:
DENFELD SUCCESS AT STATE!
Prior to the current health pandemic taking over our community's focus, the Denfeld CyberPatriot Team earned 3rd Place in the open division of the Minnesota State Competition. The team received a Certificate of Excellence in honor of the outstanding technical skill, problem solving, and teamwork demonstrated by placing among the top teams in the CP-XII State Round.
Congratulations team members: Nikolai Breimon, Charles Gilbert, and Madeline Bjonskaas. Coach: Timothy White.
CyberPatriot puts teams of high school and middle school students in the position of newly hired IT professionals managing a small company network. Teams review virtual operating system images and are tasked with finding cybersecurity vulnerabilities and hardening the system while maintaining critical services.
Thank you, Susan Johnson, for the photos and info.
#Inspire709 #HunterPride
www.ISD709.org/Denfeld

Denfeld and Duluth East High Schools join #BeTheLightMN initiative as a sign of hope, and to honor and encourage the Class of 2020, students and community. Lights at Historic Public Schools Stadium and Ordean Stadium will be on at 8:20PM for 20 minutes on Monday nights. Please enjoy from afar and respect social distancing, fields are not open to the public during this time.
From John Millea, MN State High School League, “We're all still here. We're going to be back under the lights at an event — at some point we're going to be able to gather again, and it's going to be great once we get back to that point. But I think just for now, it's just a symbol ... that there's still light out there and there's hope. And what we're going through now isn't going to last forever."
#BeTheLightMN #HunterPrideDHS #DuluthEastGreyhounds

post_text:
Many Thanks to Our ISD 709 Maintenance Staff...

DULUTH PUBLIC SCHOOLS HEROES

Dan Lane, a longtime utility department employee at Denfeld High School, said the coronavirus pandemic is "uncharted territory for everyone, including for those of us with Duluth Public Schools."

"We're regarded as essential employees, and there's things to continue to take care of -- boilers, general maintenance and such," Dan said during a break from outside work Monday. "Sanitization is a big thing right now, as we do our best to protect the people that come and go here at Denfeld. The teachers are working hard to teach their students online. The best thing we can do is take it one day at a time and hope for the best."

Duluth Public Schools photo. Click on the photo for a larger view.

Duluth School Board Selects John Magas for Final Superintendent Candidate: The vote followed a months-long process which included hiring a search firm, a public process to develop a leadership profile, input from community groups and organizations and two rounds of public interviews.
His experience includes Associate Superintendent of Continuous Improvement for the Green Bay Area School District in Wisconsin; Director of Secondary Teaching, Learning and Equity for the Sun Prairie Area School District in Wisconsin; Principal for the Appleton Area School District in Wisconsin and Assistant Principal for the Toppenish School District in Washington.
More: https://www.isd709.org/district/superintendent-search

post_text:
UPDATE: ISD 709 CORONAVIRUS RESPONSE
We just posted on www.ISD709.org/updates re: Governor's executive order to close schools to students March 18 - 27.
We'll continue to provide updates over the coming days and weeks.
• We plan to provide school for students on Monday 3/16 and Tuesday 3/17. We know there are families who may choose to keep their children home. Please call your school and it will be considered an excused absence.
• Beginning Monday 3/16, all after school activities and clubs are cancelled with the exception of the KEY Zone program. KEY Zone will remain open Monday and Tuesday.
• Consistent with the Governor’s order, the Minnesota State High School League announced that effective from March 18 through March 27 there will be no MSHSL activities and athletics at any member school.
• Before the end of the day Tuesday 3/17, families should make arrangements to pick up their child’s medication from school.
Thank you for your patience and commitment as we navigate this unprecedented situation.

DENFELD ROBOTICS TEAM QUALIFIES FOR WORLD CHAMPIONSHIP!
Denfeld Nation Automation (DNA) FIRST Robotics Team 4009 received the Engineering Inspiration Award at the Lake Superior Regional in Duluth, congratulations! This award celebrates outstanding success in advancing respect and appreciation for engineering within a team's school and community. This award also qualifies DNA for the World Championship in Detroit, Michigan April 29 - May 2. DNA had the second highest autonomous score ranking at the Lake Superior Regional, which consisted of 63 teams from all over the Midwest.
DNA extends a sincere thank you to all of their generous sponsors and supporters for making it
possible for them to compete and for everybody that came out to support and cheer.

MONDAY SPORTS NOTEBOOK

Duluth East and Denfeld softball and boys and girls track practices begin today. Baseball and boys and girls golf practices begin next Monday, followed by boys tennis on March 23 and boys and girls lacrosse on March 30.

. . .

Duluth East will face top-seeded Cambridge-Isanti in the Section 7AAAA high school boys basketball championship game at 7 p.m. Thursday at Elk River High School. The Greyhounds lost to Cambridge-Isanti twice during the regular season, 69-65 on Dec. 17 at East Gym and 83-77 on Dec. 27 at the North Star State Hardwood Showcase in Hibbing. The Greyhounds are led by 6-foot-6 junior power forward Mattie Thompson and 6-8 junior center Noah Paulson, both college prospects.

SPORTS QUOTE

New Denfeld baseball coach Joe Wicklund, a former pitcher for the Duluth-Superior Dukes and Duluth Marshall head coach, on what attracted him to the storied Hunters' program:

"The two things that really drew me to explore the Denfeld baseball job were the wonderful things happening at the school -- and the west side of the town overall -- and the connections I’d built coaching many Hunters over the last five years with the West Duluth Cubs out of American Legion Post #71. Denfeld graduated many talented players from last year’s state-bound team, but I think this group can also be a strong contender in 7AAA as we develop together through the spring season."

Denfeld begins official preseason practices Monday. Top returning players:

Outfielders Caleb Perrault, Kade Shea and Owen Johnson

Infielders Corey Graves, Joe Udd, Corey Miller, CJ Christensen and Dawson Jasper

Catchers Jace Anderson, Carter Kilroy and Nick LaFlair

Pitcher Logan Nylund

STUDENTS TRAVEL TO UMD FOR ANTI-RACIST YOUTH SUMMIT, GREENHOUSE TOUR!
Students from the Duluth Area Learning Center took a field trip to the University of MN - Duluth for the first ever Anti-Racist Youth Summit. Students explored racism, racial identity and culture with 150 local youth and heard from fabulous speakers, including Naawakwe/William Howes from the ISD 709 Office of Education Equity. Afterward the summit students toured the UMD greenhouse to learn about botany, check out Freckles the resident box turtle and create biospheres to take home. Many thanks to the ALC, Office of Education Equity, Duluth NAACP and UMD for making this trip possible.
#Inspire709
www.ISD709.org/Area-Learning-Center

DOUBLE DECC'er REGIONAL HIGH SCHOOL ROBOTICS COMPETITION MARCH 5-7!
Known as the largest FIRST Robotics Competition held under one roof, the Double DECC’er combines the Northern Lights Regional and Lake Superior Regional. Both host over 60 teams - one coming from Sweden!
Join the Duluth East Daredevils, Denfeld DNA, Two Harbors Rock Solid Robotics, Hermantown Talon Robotics, Marshall TopperBots and many more area teams! The event is open to the public, and free for all spectators. It takes place at - no surprise - the DECC in Duluth.

Duluth East has earned the No. 2 seed and will host Anoka (4-22) in a Section 7AAAA high school boys basketball quarterfinal at 7 p.m. Wednesday.

The Greyhounds and Tornadoes did not play during the regular season. Anoka has lost 12 straight.

Duluth East is led by junior power forward Mattie Thompson, 6-8 junior center Noah Paulson, sophomore guard Will Van Scoy, junior guard Giovani Saldivar and senior guard-forward Noah Winesett. Junior guard Zaa Buffalo has been a strong contributor off the bench.

Top-seeded Cambridge-Isanti (22-4), which defeated the Greyhounds (22-4) twice during the regular season, has received a first-round bye into the semifinals.

Meanwhile, Denfeld (4-22) will visit top-seeded Princeton (22-4) in a Section 7AAA quarterfinal on Wednesday at 7 p.m.

The Hunters are led by seniors Armon Freeman and Josh Reinertsen.

SPORTS NOTEBOOK

Duluth East will play host to Denfeld in a high school boys basketball game at 7 p.m. today, as both teams close out the 2019-20 regular season.

The Greyhounds defeated the Hunters 85-71 on December 19 at Denfeld Gym, with Mattie Thompson and Noah Paulson scoring 23 points each for East (21-4).

Josh Reinertsen had a game-high 35 points and teammate Armon Freeman added 28 points for Denfeld (4-21).

Other key players to watch tonight:

Greyhounds: Giovani Saldivar, Will Van Scoy, Noah Winesett

Hunters: Jon Bongiovanni, Nino Franklin

Duluth East will host a Section 7AAAA first-round quarterfinal Wednesday at 7 p.m. against a yet-to-be-determined opponent, while Denfeld will open Section 7AAA play Tuesday at 7 p.m. on the road.

Duluth Public Schools Photo

THANK YOU, DULUTH SCHOOL BUS DRIVERS!
February 26 is Minnesota School Bus Driver Appreciation Day, honoring those who take on the important job of getting students to and from school safely each day (in Duluth, that's thousands of students!).
From Governor Tim Walz's proclamation: "In darkness and daylight, on dirt roads and multi-lane highways, from the rainy late spring to the frigid winter, Minnesota school bus drivers safely transport more than 760,000 students to and from school each day...bus drivers bookend a student's school day, serving as a mentor and having a positive influence on a student's educational experience."
#Inspire709 #ThankABusDriver
www.ISD709.org

DENFELD, LINCOLN PARK TEACHERS SEMIFINALISTS FOR 2020 MN TEACHER OF THE YEAR!
Congratulations to Nicole Jensen, Lincoln Park Middle School and Brian Jungman, Denfeld High School, chosen as semifinalists from an initial field of 135 candidates from across the state. A panel of community leaders will review the semifinalists’ portfolios and video submissions in late March and will select about 10 finalists from among the group. The 2020 Minnesota Teacher of the Year will be announced in May at a special event in St. Paul.
The Minnesota Teacher of the Year program, now in its 56th year, is the oldest and most prestigious recognition program in Minnesota to honor excellence in education. The program chooses one teacher to represent Minnesota's thousands of excellent educators.
#Inspire709 #ExcellenceInEducation #DuluthTeachersRock
Press Release: https://bit.ly/32rXxEx
www.ISD709.org

ALC WILDERNESS ELITE WINTER CAMPING!
Duluth Area Learning Center Wilderness Elite students stayed overnight at Bear Head Lake State Park in Ely. They practiced building fires and cooking campfire meals outdoors, they played games, snowshoed, walked out on the frozen lake and spent the night in rustic cabins. They toured the Tower Soudan Mine and visited the International Wolf Center. Everyone had a wonderful time participating in this quality alternative educational experience. The trip was made possible with support from the ALC, The Office of Education Equity, and a grant from the Harbor Town Rotary, many thanks for their support.
#Inspire709
www.ISD709.org/Area-Learning-Center

post_text:
DULUTH EAST RECEIVES GAPP SCHOOL OF DISTINCTION AWARD!
The German American Partnership Program “School of Distinction” Award recognizes outstanding GAPP Schools in the U.S. for their engagement and best practices that facilitate global citizenship in their schools, communities, and beyond. Duluth East GAPP coordinators and teachers Lynn Hinzmann and Emily Lull will be recognized for their work with GAPP during the school's Red and Grey Week assembly.
For 22 years, Duluth East has successfully developed and integrated the GAPP program in grades 9-12 with support from the School Board, families, students, and the Duluth community. Duluth East and partner schools have hosted over 450 German students, and over 350 American students have traveled to stay with exchange partners in Germany.
#Inspire709 #HerzlicheGlückwünsche
www.ISD709.org/Duluth-East

VIRTUAL REALITY INSPIRES DENFELD, DULUTH EAST STUDENTS!
With help from the College of St. Scholastica, medical occupation students used virtual reality to learn more about being a Physician Assistant and how the heart works.
In one program, a large, 3-D version of a beating heart could be manipulated and studied using virtual reality. Another program took students inside a clinic to observe while a professional Physician Assistant worked with a patient. Duluth East principal Danette Seboe stopped by the classroom and tried out the virtual reality gear, too. Thank you, CSS, for the opportunity!
#Inspire709 #CareerTechEdMonth

Governor Tim Walz
February 10 at 10:59 PM ·

I’m honored to proclaim February as Black History Month in Minnesota to recognize the generations of African Americans who have risked their lives for justice and who continue to fight for equality today.

Here in Minnesota, I want to thank and uplift the work of the United Black Legislative Caucus, who are dedicated to addressing the racial disparities in our state.

MONDAY ACTIVITIES

5 p.m. -- Duluth East hockey at Eagan. Game Notes: The Greyhounds (9-11-2) look to finish the regular season with victories in their final two regular season games, including Tuesday's game at Superior. Junior forward Zarley Ziemski leads East with 14 goals, and senior forward Charlie Erickson has a team-high 25 points (12 goals). Ziemski and senior defenseman Ryan Cummings are second in scoring with 21 points each. Senior goaltender Konrad Kausch has been rock solid, with a 2.96 goals-against average and .902 saves percentage.

7 p.m. -- Duluth East boys basketball at Blaine. Game Notes: The Greyhounds (15-4) have won nine of their last 11, including two straight. East will also play host to Forest Lake on Thursday and Hastings Saturday. Greyhounds scoring leaders, per game, are junior guard Mattie Thompson (19.4), junior center Noah Paulson (14.8), sophomore point guard Will Van Scoy (13.5) and senior guard Noah Winesett (12.3).

RECOGNITION FOR LAURA MACARTHUR STUDENT POETRY!
Fourth and fifth grade students at Laura MacArthur Elementary had an opportunity to participate in poetry contest built around Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.’s quote “I am the dream.” The contest was sponsored by the school's Student Council.
Building upon Dr. King’s passion and leadership, students were encouraged to creatively express ways to work together to generate opportunities to better themselves and society as a whole.
Congratulations to 1st, 2nd and 3rd Place Award recipients and to all students who submitted their work! Thank you, Calvin Harris, for the photo and information.
#Inspire709
www.ISD709.org/Laura-MacArthur

THANK YOU, DULUTH COACHES & ADVISERS!
Governor Tim Walz proclaimed January 27 - February 2, 2020 as Thank A Coach/Adviser Week (apologies for the late post)!
Please take a moment to thank the folks who work hard to provide students opportunities outside the classroom.
In our Duluth Public Schools, students soar to new heights in athletics, art, speech, theater, debate, knowledge bowl, robotics, clubs, boards and dozens of other opportunities in a variety of interests and areas. These activities help make our Duluth schools special.
Studies show extracurricular activities can enhance student success across multiple areas, including higher grade point averages, better attendance at school, and character development. The impact of coaches and advisers is an asset to their professions, students, school districts, and local communities.
#Inspire709 #ThankACoach #ThankAnAdviser
www.ISD709.org

post_text:
COMMUNITY PROVIDES FREE BOOKS FOR STOWE STUDENTS!
Many thanks to Fran Morris, GND REC - Gary New Duluth Recreation Center and volunteers who provide a wonderful opportunity for students at Stowe Elementary. Through their I Love To Read event nearly 1,000 new and gently used books are provided to children at Stowe. They bring each class to the REC, provide a snack, read a story and then students can pick out two brand new books and two gently used books. This year students also got a chance to check out a police squad used by the Duluth Police Department.
Readers include Duluth Police Chief Mike Tusken, several Duluth police officers and assistant superintendent Jeff Horton. Thanks to all for their support of students and schools.
#Inspire709 #LoveToRead #CommunitySupport
www.ISD709.org/Stowe-Elementary

Many thanks to our Duluth Public School paraprofessionals for the support they provide in our schools and for making a positive difference for every child, every day.
#Inspire709

STATEBOUND DENFELD MUSIC LISTENING TEAM!
Congratulations Logan Griggs, Phoenix Ocean and Aidan Anderson, they took First Place in the MN High School Music Listening regional competition with a high score of 84/100. They move on to the State competition in February.
This is the "Knowledge Bowl of Music," contest materials cover classical music, global perspectives, and a variety of musical influences.
Kudos to all Denfeld Music Listening Team members and their adviser Clare Chopp:
Keziah Pop, Madison McKean, A'staria Perry, Josie Nichols, Eric Stolee, Annika Swanson, Ariana Wisniewski, Haven Anderson, Ella Ruble, Sam Gilbert, Hanna Hovland, Cassandra Franzen, Acacia Novy.

post_text:
Mushing Morrows!
Sawyer and Hazel are students in Misaabekong at Lowell Elementary and have been mushing sled dogs for three years. This is something that they enjoy doing and take pride in the native culture and history that the sport represents in this region.
In the 2020 Cub Run, Sawyer placed 1st in the 2.6 mile race with Elmer and Earhardt and Hazel tied for 2nd in the 1.5 mile race with Earhardt and Battleship, congratulations!
As part of the Cub Run awards ceremony Sawyer presented (in both English and Ojibwe) the 7 Grandfather Teachings to his 20 fellow mushers (ages 3-12 years old), he did a great job sharing his language and knowledge with others.
Thank you, Edye Binesiikwe Washington, for the information and thank you, Ambers Impressions, for the photos.
Sawyer's GoPro Video: : https://youtu.be/7zqx-PuplK4
#Inspire709
www.ISD709.org/Misaabekong

post_text: The Duluth Northern Stars high school girls hockey team is scheduled to play its two final games of the regular season this week: Tuesday night at Grand Rapids/Greenway and Thursday night at home against Moose Lake Area. The Northern Stars are led in scoring by sophomore forward Annika Lindgren, who has 14 goals and 31 points. Senior goaltender Sarah Spencer is also having a strong season with seven victories and two shutouts. Pictured, from left to right, are Northern Star standouts Elaina Benson, Hannah Martin, Bianca Lott and Ella McCarthy.
